Predicting Expected Goals Tallies of Soccer Players with Machine Learning¶

By Vikas Thoti Reddy¶

Introduction¶

Predicting the expected goal tallies of top players in the upcoming season in soccer with machine learning is a fresh way of calculating the metric. I use the player's current market value, age, and statistics from their previous two seasons (goals, assists, and minutes played) to predict their expected goal tally in the upcoming season (2022-2023). In soccer, goals are the currency of the game and the ability to predict which players are likely to score more goals can give teams a significant advantage.

One of the key benefits of using machine learning techniques to predict expected goal tally is that it allows for a more accurate prediction. Traditional methods of predicting goal tally, such as using past performance or subjective assessments, can be prone to bias and are not always reliable. On the other hand, machine learning algorithms are able to analyze large amounts of data and intricate identify patterns that traditional analysis can't. For example, one can assume an approximately concave and quadtratic average relationship between age and goals scored. There is a peak in each player's career where they performed the best; however, at what age this peak occurs and by how much is difficult to measure. Using machine learning algorithms to leverage these mathmatical relationships for prediction is the key.

Overall, using machine learning allows for a more objective and statistical assessment of player performance. In soccer, there is often a lot of subjectivity around how players are valued and how they are perceived to be performing. Machine learning algorithms provide a more unbiased way of evaluating player performance, which can help teams make more informed decisions about which players to sign and how to use them on the field. This can give teams a significant advantage on the field. This has the potential to revolutionize the way that soccer is played and analyzed.

Data Processing and Cleaning¶

The data for this project is from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/davidcariboo/player-scores.

  1. Loading the data from the CSV files. The data was separated into separate datasets (player appearances, player info, club info, and competition info.
  2. Merged and cleaned these various datasets to get a cummulative dataframe including the information from each individual dataset. I achieved this by merging and aggregating statistics based on player ID (There are different players with the same name in these datasets). Player ID was a unique identifier.
  3. Cummulated the appearances dataset to get the statistics for each player (goals, assists, minutes played, yellow cards, red cards)
  4. Used the player dataset to get details of each player (current market value in gbp, height, strong foot, date of birth, position, current club)
  5. Used the clubs dataset to match the domestic league that each player plays in.

There were some small errors in the dataset. Some players had outdated club teams. For example, the dataset says that Cristiano Ronaldo still plays for Juventus; however, he has been playing for Machester United since the start of the 2021-2022 season. Other players had mislabeled positions. For example, Kevin De Bruyne and Bruno Fernandes were labeled as attackers even though they should most definately be objectively labeled at midfielders. In the grand scheme of the ML model that is used for prediction, these errors do not impact model performance.

full_player_stats = full_player_stats.sort_values("date")

Data, Training, and Testing Methodology¶

Here, I curate the merged dataset to create features that may be useful to predict expected goal tallies. For the machine learning data pipeline, I plan to use statistics from the 2018-2019 and 2019-2020 seasons and market value from the start of the 2020-2021 to predict the expected goal tallies during the 2020-2021 season. I plan on testing my prediction with the actual goal tallies from the 2020-2021 season. Then, I will train and test the models on this sample data with a 10-fold cross validation. From the cross validation results and further analysis, I will chose one model. From here, after picking a final model based on the results of the cross validation and testing, I will use statistics from the 2020-2021 and 2021-2022 seasons (data that the model has not been trained on) to predict the expected goal tallies of the upcoming 2022-2023.

In addition, in this section, I calculate the age of each player in days and years, aggregate the goals, assists, minutes played, yellow cards, and red cards for each player from the start of the 2018-2019 season to the end of the 2019-2020 season. I chose to only include players who have played more than 2000 minutes (roughly 20 games) over the course of the 2018-2019 and 2019-2020 seasons. This was reasonable as we don't want players that play a statistically insignificant amount of games to bias the machine learning model. Furthermore, from the 2020-2021 dataset that I create below, I extract market value and age; moreover, I calculate the actual goal tallies during the 2020-2021 season for testing.

Standardizing Inputs¶

At this point, after some analysis, I have chosen to use 5 different features (goals, assists, and minutes played in the previous 2 seasons, and current age and market value) to predict expected goal tallies. I decide to standardize goals, assists, age, and market value to a z-score with the mean and standard deviation of each feature. Speficically, I noticed the the market value is heavily inflated as the youngest and most talented players have a very high market value. The reasoning behind this is to see wether standardizing these values may have an impact on model logic or performance.

In [10]:
# changing market value to a z_score
all_positions["market_value_z_score"] = all_positions["market_value_in_gbp"] - all_positions["market_value_in_gbp"].mean()  
all_positions["market_value_z_score"] /= all_positions["market_value_in_gbp"].std()
all_positions["market_value_z_score"]

# changing age to a z_score
all_positions["age_d_start_2020_season_z"] = all_positions["age_d_start_2020_season"] 
all_positions["age_d_start_2020_season_z"] -= all_positions["age_d_start_2020_season"].mean()  
all_positions["age_d_start_2020_season_z"] /= all_positions["age_d_start_2020_season"].std()

# changing market value to a z_score
all_positions["goals_z"] = all_positions["goals"] - all_positions["goals"].mean()  
all_positions["goals_z"] /= all_positions["goals"].std()

# changing age to a z_score
all_positions["assists_z"] = all_positions["assists"] - all_positions["assists"].mean()  
all_positions["assists_z"] /= all_positions["assists"].std()

Initial Analysis¶

Here, I take a look at the relationships between some of the features that I selected. This helped me understand what type of model may be most beneficial to use. I examine linear and catagorical relationships to understand the interaction between each feature in the dataset.

There seems to be a roughly concave and quadratic relationship between age and market value. However, the graph is heavily inflated by players who had a low market value over the course of their careers. Market value is determined by a player's percieved value (influenced by performance, age, nation, etc..). The market value of a player should be an important feature in the final machine learning model that I choose.

Finally, in this section, I looked at the strength of the relationships between features in the dataset after separating by position. I noticed that predicting expected goal tallies for attackers would be the easiest. For attackers, their market value and past statistics are more strictly related to future goal tallies. There are imeasurable factors and additional features not in the dataset (ex. clean sheets, key passes, successful dribbles) that would determine the performance of midfielders, defenders, and goalkeepers. After this initial anlysis, I decided to soley predict the expected goal tallies for attackers.

Hypothesis¶

After my initial analysis, I chose to use a linear regression to create my predictions for expected goal tallies. I opted for a linear regression over a decision tree regression and random forest regression. I think the decision tree regression and random forest regression may have a decent r^2 score and mean_squared_error, but may not catch the linear relationships between the features and target variable. In addition, I predict that the model that uses standardized features will more accurately catch the linear relationships in he data.

Findings from the initial analysis:

  1. There is a roughly concave and quadratic relationship between age and market value
  2. There is a rough linear relationship between market value and goals scored in the past two seasons
  3. The domestic league that a player plays in influences their percieved market value

Training¶

To train the data, I use a 70-30 training and testing split and a 10-fold cross validation. To score the models, I use r^2 and root mean squared error (RMSE). r^2 is expected to be low as there was signficant variance in the dataset; however, the model with standardized features will attempt to overcome the high variance and outliers present in the data.

# mode feature importance function that looks at coefficient of linear regression
def model_feature_importance(coef, names):
    imp = coef
    imp,names = zip(*sorted(zip(imp,names)))
    plt.barh(range(len(names)), imp, align='center')
    plt.yticks(range(len(names)), names)
    plt.ylabel("Feature")
    plt.xlabel("Model Coefficient")
    plt.show()

Predicting Current Season¶

The linear regression model that used standardized inputs performed better and will be the final model used to predict the expected goal tallies for the 2021-2022 season. Both regression models had a r^2 around 0.54 and a RMSE of around 5.29; however, the models calculated the prediction very differently. The regression model with non standardized inputs almost soley used the goals tally from the last two seasons to predict a player's future expected goal tally. This is unreasonable as at some point in a player's career their goal tally will decrease. A model that uses other features to make a prediction will be more realistic and perform better on out-of-sample data. The regression model with standardized inputs used multiple features and caught onto to the relationships between features. For example, according to the model, a player who's market value decreases because of factors not described in the dataset will be expected to score fewer goals. This makes sense and can be applied in the real world for out of sample predictions. However, the model says that as players age, they score more goals. This is not entirely true, but a linear model cannot be expected to capture the quadratic relationship between age and performance. This can be a source of future research. In conclusion, I chose to use the regression model that used standardized inputs as it catches the relationship between the features and the target variable more accurately.

# Creating dataset to make a prediction about the 2022-2023 (upcoming/current) season

# Cummulating data from last two seasons 2020-2021, 2021-2022
start_datetime = datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 15)
end_datetime = datetime.datetime(2022, 6, 1)
final_df = full_player_stats.loc[full_player_stats["date"] > start_datetime]
final_df = final_df.loc[final_df["date"] < end_datetime]

# calculate player age at start of current season for final model prediction
start_datetime = datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 15)
final_df['date_of_birth'] = final_df['date_of_birth'].astype(str)
final_df['date_of_birth'] = pd.to_datetime(final_df['date_of_birth'])
final_df["age_d_start_2022_season"] = (start_datetime - final_df['date_of_birth']).astype('timedelta64[D]')
final_df["age_y_start_2022_season"] = (start_datetime - final_df['date_of_birth']).astype('timedelta64[Y]')

# summing stats for players across their appearences in selected competitions
sum_stats = ["goals", "assists", "minutes_played", "yellow_cards", "red_cards"]
final_df_sum = final_df.groupby("player_id")[sum_stats].sum()
final_df_sum = final_df_sum.sort_values("goals", ascending=False)

# capturing player info data that does not need aggregating
details = ["pretty_name", "country_of_citizenship", "foot", "height_in_cm", "club_id", "club_name", 
           "domestic_competition_id","position", "market_value_in_gbp", "highest_market_value_in_gbp",
           "age_d_start_2022_season", "age_y_start_2022_season", "competition_name"]
def detail(x):
    return x[0]
final_df_details = final_df.groupby("player_id")[details]
final_df_details = final_df_details.agg(lambda col: np.sort(col.unique()).tolist())
for col in final_df_details.columns:
    final_df_details[col] = final_df_details[col].apply(detail)

# merging data into one dataframe
final_df = final_df_details.merge(final_df_sum, left_index=True, right_index=True)
final_df = final_df.dropna()
final_df = final_df.sort_values("goals", ascending=False)
final_df = final_df.loc[final_df["minutes_played"] > 3000]

# changing market value to a z_score
final_df["market_value_z_score"] = final_df["market_value_in_gbp"] - final_df["market_value_in_gbp"].mean()  
final_df["market_value_z_score"] /= final_df["market_value_in_gbp"].std()

# changing age to z_score
final_df["age_d_start_2022_season_z"] = final_df["age_d_start_2022_season"] - final_df["age_d_start_2022_season"].mean()  
final_df["age_d_start_2022_season_z"] /= final_df["age_d_start_2022_season"].std()

# changing market value to a z_score
final_df["goals_z"] = final_df["goals"] - final_df["goals"].mean()  
final_df["goals_z"] /= final_df["goals"].std()

# changing age to a z_score
final_df["assists_z"] = final_df["assists"] - final_df["assists"].mean()  
final_df["assists_z"] /= final_df["assists"].std()

# calculate statistics and sort data
final_df["goal_contr_last2_seasons"] = final_df["goals"] + final_df["assists"]
final_df = final_df.sort_values("goal_contr_last2_seasons", ascending=False)

Discussion of Results¶

At first look, the players predicted to have the highest goal tallies are the best players in the world. In addition, the top players on this list are on track to reach their expected goal tallies. There are no surprises in the top 15. Furthermore, if I were to make a subjective list of who I think will score the most goals this season, my list would look very similar to the list created by the regression model. Surprisingly, the results from the model match the predictions that sports analysts from ESPN made at the beginning of the season (https://www.espn.com/soccer/english-premier-league/story/4712376/premier-leaguelaligabundesliga-2022-23-season-predictions-most-yellow-cardstop-scorersrelegation-and-more).

On a separete note, the model seems to punish players with impecable track records who have hit retirement age (Lionel Messi, Cristiano Ronaldo, and Karim Benzema). Similar to the model, in real life, from a subjective analysis, the named players are expected to decline. This has probobly occured because the market values for these aging legends has probably declined signficantly; in turn, the model is predicting a lower expected goal tally.

As for right now, the results show all good signs and no surprises; however, at the end of this season in June 2023, I am curious to see the comparison between the expected goal tallies from the regression and the actual goal tallies for this season.
